did.unittitle: Howard Gillette Collection on the Italian American Community of Washington, D.C.
did.abstract: Collection consists of a significant number of photographs collected from the exhibit "Washington's Italian Community 1890-Present" developed and sponsored by the Washington Area Studies Department that was held in November 1984; negatives of all materials collected; obituaries; news articles; research notes; correspondence; clippings; and copies of the exhibit flyer and the article Alan Kraut and Howard Gillette did for the "Journal of American Ethnic History."

prefercite.head: Preferred citation
prefercite.p: Howard Gillette Collection on the Italian American Community of Washington, D.C., Special Collections Research Center, The George Washington University.

userestrict.head: Restrictions on Use
userestrict.p: Some material may be copyrighted or restricted. It is the patron's obligation to determine and satisfy copyright or other case restrictions when publishing or otherwise distributing materials found in the collections.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The exhibit "Washington's Italian Community 1890-Present" developed and sponsored by the Washington Area Studies Department, was held in November 1984. Alan Kraut and Howard Gillette wrote an article for the "Journal of American Ethnic History" related to the exhibit.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This is a collection of materials from the exhibit "Washington's Italian Community 1890-Present" developed and sponsored by the Washington Area Studies Department that was held in November 1984. The collection consists of a significant number of photographs collected from the exhibit, negatives of all materials collected, obituaries, news articles, research notes, correspondence, and other clippings, and copies of the exhibit flyer and the article Alan Kraut and Howard Gillette did for the "Journal of American Ethnic History."

Clipping from The Hill Rag, 01/09/1984, on Litteri's, a deli on Morse Street between 6th Street and Florida Avenue NE. Business opened by Antonio Litteri, who arrived in the U.S. in 1926, lived briefly in New York, and then came to D.C., where he stationed a produce wagon in the market at 16th and K NW. In 1932 he moved to the present shop. He had no children, so his brother-in-law Mariano De Francisci took over, and now De Francisci's sons. Clipping from the Washington Post, 12/12/1972, Betty Medsger, "Area Italians Proud of Accomplishments." Highlights the Catania Bakery 1404 North Capitol Street (we went by it on our way to and from the John Paul II Cultural Center), which the Caruso family opened on Labor Day 1932. It supplies bread for the Villa Rosa fall festival. Also the Italian Groceries Store, 1317 Pennsylvania Avenue, run by Anna Mangialardo and her son Antonio. She was born in the United States, the daughter of a coal miner who went back to Italy with her family as a child and then came back to the United States with her husband
